Jeff Sessions could have saved the end of his drug speech for the beginning. And he could have saved it for a speech in Nashville. Or Knoxville. Or Chattanooga.
But then again when youre trying to drum up support for harsh largely ineffective penalties for drug crimes a mostly-black city like Memphis is a convenient stage for playing to fears.
The attorney general singled out Memphis violent crime rate in a speech earlier this month  one in which he announced that he was in effect reinstating the mandatory minimum sentencing policies that the Justice Department had halted under the Obama administration.
Then yesterday Sessions visited Memphis to double-down on that talk about how horrible the violence was here how bad the drugs were here and how his people werent going to put up with it.
On the violence hes right.
Last year 228 people were killed in Memphis  195 of which were classified as murders. That rate mirrors the violence that wracked the city in the 1990s.
Ironically that violence happened during the height of the crack cocaine epidemic and during a time when mandatory minimum sentences  the approach that Sessions wants to revive  were ramped up to deal with the problem.
They didnt work then  and they wont work now.
All those harsh sentences did was create an environment where one in nine black children now have a parent in prison and where a prior record for having the tiniest amounts of drugs shuts off virtually all chances of getting a job or a place to live.
That predicament is a huge part of whats driving the poverty and despair behind the violence in Memphis and its something that Sessions policies would exacerbate.
Yet if Sessions aim was to put a fright in people about dying from drugs or crimes related to drugs he could have done that on the other side of Tennessee  because in Nashville 367 people died in 2015 from opioid overdoses. In Chattanooga 183 people died from such overdoses while in Knoxville those deaths stood at 325.
All combined the drug deaths in those predominantly-white cities totaled 875. Those are the places that have for the most part helped to make Tennessee the state with the second highest rate of opioid abuse in the nation  next to Sessions home state of Alabama.
He talked about that problem  toward the end.
There is no doubt in my mind thatthe surge of heroin and opioid abuse will bring with it a surge in crime Sessions said. I was in New Hampshirethere were 50 mothers on the stage who had lost kids to opioid abuse.
But said local activist Tami Sawyer who protested Sessions visit along with hundreds of others his mention of the opioid issue was a sop to white people who believe he will treat their problem more as a sickness than as a crime.
To me its a buzzword because they know that their children will be cared for but for us hes talking about putting more cops on the streets to arrest people for having marijuana Sawyer said. But whats killing people is heroinwhats killing people are opioids
Hes Sessions not going to Nashville to raise money and our leaders here theyre running on fear.
Shes right.
By continuing to single out Memphis for its drug-related violence to justify ramping up a drug war that made it worse as opposed to going to Nashville or Knoxville or Chattanooga to hammer them about their opioid and heroin problems Sessions does more to play to fears about black criminality than to ideas about how to fix the problem.
And while its sad that Sessions is using Memphians suffering as a platform to revive draconian approaches to drugs and violence crime it will be even sadder if officials remain silent as he does so.
