The Memphis Police Department's Organized Crime Unit said police investigated 12 suspected overdose incidents within the last 24 hours.
Of the 12 people who are suspected to have overdosed two have died.
Officials with the Shelby County Health Department say that opioid-overdose related deaths are now occurring at an average rate of 20 every month.
In just the last seven days seven overdose-related deaths have occurred in Shelby County.
Col. Paul Wright stressed that he wants anyone with a drug addiction not to fear prosecution.
We're not about picking up a user Wright said If you are a user don't be scared to call for assistance.
Police say there is no one form of opioids that is causing overdose deaths.
In the last 24 hours investigators have seen overdoses that are linked to opioids in pill form as well as heroin injected intravenously.
