The Local I-Team investigates the growing heroin problem in Shelby County.
As of this week 21 people have died of heroin overdoses in Shelby County since the beginning of the year.
Police are calling it an epidemic.
The problem is so bad Memphis police have changed how officers handle overdoses. In an effort to track heroin sellers the Organized Crime Unit now takes over all investigations involving heroin overdose deaths. Families of those who have died want dealers off the streets so more lives wont be lost.
Two local families are now suffering after both 19-year-old Brennan Rucker and 22-year-old Crystal Gabriesheski died of whats believed to be heroin overdoses. Rucker passed away in December Gabriesheski last month. The two were good friends.
I feel angry hurt said Cassie Milam Gabriesheskis aunt.
I do not wish this pain on any person said Ruckers mother Kristen Mitchell. Its unfortunate because these are good kids that made bad decisions.
Both grew up in Memphis suburbs came from good families and died within two months of each other. Neither family knew about the heroin.
I wish so much now I would have been aware and able to be there for her said Milam.
In both cases the families say if the people the teens were with had called 911 for help sooner they may have survived.
Ruckers mom says her sons friends waited an hour while he was overdosing before dumping him at an emergency room and driving off.
They did not call 911. Instead they decided to freak out and panic said Mitchell.
Gabriesheskis family says her friends didnt call 911 until they put her in a car and drove her away from the drug dealers home.
We were told if they would have just called 911 she could have been saved said Milam.
According to Memphis police last year 27 people died of heroin overdoses. So far in 2016 21 people have already died which is why Memphis police now handle the deaths as investigations. Many of the victims are in their late teens or early twenties.
Talk to your kids. Be involved. Ask questions. Annoy them. Its your job as a parent. Find out what is going on with them said Mitchell.
In Ruckers case his mother finds some comfort knowing her sons heart still beats in Memphis.
Brennan actually signed up to be an organ donor and was able to save six lives as a result said Mitchell.
Gabriesheskis family wants justice and has a message to those who were there that fatal night.
Please talk to the police. Please let them know. Im and asking and begging you so myself and my family can be at peace and rest said Milam.
