David Fuller a Regional Overdose Prevention Specialist with the Memphis Area Prevention Coalition runs trainings and facilities access to resources that can empower an individual to know what to do when someone is experiencing an overdose and possibly prevent a death.
He talked to The Commercial Appeal about resources facts and myths around overdoses and preventing fatalities.
Who is at risk for exposure to fentanyl
In short nearly anybody.
Fentanyl is most commonly associated with opioid abuse but that association is an incomplete picture.
It's not a new drug but it's popularity on the streets has soared since 2011 because it makes drugs more powerful and cheaper to produce. Illicit dealers are adding fentanyl to cocaine and methamphetamines  i.e. meth crank ice. Addiction specialists have noted it's prevalent in counterfeit drugs. In some cases it's been found in marijuana.
According to the state department of health it is now the number one substance driving fatal overdoses and is responsible for more than 50 of deaths. Its prevalence means that it's not only individuals with active addictions that are at risk of knowingly or unknowingly consuming fentanyl  it is also claiming the lives of individuals in Tennessee who may buy a single counterfeit pill or try a drug for the first time.
All demographics Fuller said are vulnerable to fentanyl overdoses. Trends among demographics may change over time but the nature of the problem continues to grow and expand. It could affect anyone. So therefore the solution needs to be available to everyone.
What can I do to avoid overdosing on fentanyl
The only surefire way to avoid fentanyl exposure is to not consume illicit drugs. Outside of complete abstinence  naloxone more commonly known by the brand name Narcan is an FDA-approved medication that will rapidly reverse an overdose.
Narcan was recently approved for over-the-counter sale nationally. Organizations in Memphis and Shelby County have been organizing trainings around its application and distributing Narcan for free to anyone interested in keeping it on hand.
Though Narcan is available over the counter at drugstores like CVS or Walgreens consumers will have to pay out of pocket for the medication.
Where can I find free Narcan in Shelby County
The exact number of organizations that provide free Narcan fluctuates as some nonprofits or churches may offer the occasional training session. But there are a handful of organizations that offer regular access to training Narcan or both. Those organizations are listed below.
Memphis Area Prevention Coalition offers training and Narcan. You can reach out to Fuller directly at 901-484-2852 or email him at davidmemphisprevention.org.
The Shelby County Health Department will sometimes offer overdose harm reduction kits and other resources. On June 10 from 10 a.m. until 2 p.m. health department employees will be handing out these kits at the Hickory Hill Community Center as part of the Background Friendly Career Fair. Each kit will contain two doses of naloxone nasal spray and 10 fentanyl test strips.
A Betor Way is an independent nonprofit that offers a range of harm reduction tools including Narcan fentanyl test strips and clean needle exchanges. For more information about their services email lisaabetorway.org.
Tennessee REDLINE is a hotline people can call to access information about inpatient treatment and detox for substance abuse disorders. You can call or text 800-889-9789 for confidential referrals.
