What will win the battle against the opioid crisis is neighbor-to-neighbor friend-to-friend family member-to-family member impact.
So when we talk about the opioid crisis in Tennessee we must always remember that amongst all the statistics  and there are plenty  that what were trying to do is save a life The life of your neighbor your Bible study group friend your mother your brother the parent of your childs classmate that you nod hello to at drop-off and pick-up.
In 2017 Tennessee providers wrote 94.4 opioid prescriptions for every 100 persons the third highest prescribing rate in the country. The good news This represents a 25-percent decline in the states opioid prescribing rate since 2013 according to the Center for Disease Control.
In Tennessee data from the state Department of Health shows 1776 Tennesseans died from drug overdoses in 2017 with prescription opioids continuing to be the most common drugs associated with overdose deaths. The data also showed a 12 percent decrease in deaths involving prescription opioids in 2017 from 2016 which is significant progress in one year.
The event will be a comprehensive overview of the effects of opioid abuse
Many are stepping up their efforts. For instance Cigna has reduced opioid prescriptions by 25 and is working to reduce opioid overdoses 25 by 2020.
Also at Methodist we have seen a 21 decrease in opioid prescriptions at discharge and a 35 decrease in the emergency room department.
However there is still a significant amount of work for all of us to do.
Thats why the West Tennessee Opioid Summit is so important. Together with Common Table Health Alliance Leadership Tennessee and the Shelby County Health Department the public is invited to the West Tennessee Opioid Summit on April 30 from 830 a.m. to 145 p.m. at the FedEx Event Center at Shelby Farms Park. The Summit is free to register visit www.leadershiptennessee.orgopioidsummit.
Sponsored by Cigna which is committed to being a national leader in prevention and treatment of opioid abuse the event will be a comprehensive overview of the effects of opioid abuse specifically in western Tennessee and Memphis.
Cross-sector groups will provide real-time solutions
Shelby County Health Department Director Dr. Alisa Haushalter DNP RN PHNA-BC will deliver the keynote address and others will share the local impact and response to the opioid epidemic including perspectives from clinicians criminal justice public policy business and personal experience.
Following speaker presentations participants will work in cross-sector groups to provide real-time solutions and innovations to existing support systems in West Tennessee.
Because whats going to crush this crisis is the direct impact we can have with those in our lives suffering from the disease of addiction and it is our hope that the conversation will empower participants to impact the response to the opioid crisis in their own community directly.
Join us April 30 for this critical conversation.
