MEMPHIS Tenn. -- Elvis Presley was a drug addict and was hospitalized under a false name for treatment of drug abuse in 1973 a jury was told Friday.
An internal medicine specialist gave details of Presley's bouts with drugs after labeling as 'outrageous and dangerous' the supply of narcotics Presley allegedly received from his physician during the last two years and seven months of the rock 'n' roll king's life.
Advertisement
Dr. George Nichopoulos Presley's doctor of 11 years is on trial on 14 felony counts of overprescribing addictive drugs to Presley singer Jerry Lee Lewis himself and eight others.
If convicted on all counts he could be sentenced to 140 years in prison fined 280000 and lose his medical license.
Prosecutor James Wilson asked Dr. Alvin Cummins to characterize Nichopoulos practices of prescribing 19000 uppers downers and painkillers for Presley over the 30-month period.
Advertisement
'They constituted an outrageous and dangerous overuse of drugs' Cummins said.
Referring to medical records Cummins revealed under the questioning of prosecutors that Presley was hospitalized three different times for a total of 48 days between Oct. 15 1973 and Sept. 25 1975.
Cummins said the records showed that Presley was treated at Baptist Hospital from Oct. 15 until Nov. 1 1973 from Jan. 28 to Feb. 13 1975 and from Aug. 21 to Sept. 25 1975.
Wilson asked Cummins about notations from consulting physicians during the first hospitalization.
'Can you tell me what they were doing' Wilson asked.
'They were withdrawing him from narcotic drugs' Cummins answered.
The trial ended its third week with defense attorney James Neal attempting an cross-examination pointing to notes in Presley's hospital charts that showed Nichopoulos ordered placebos in place of hard drugs.
Cummins agreed that placebos were given on occasion but testified that Nichopoulos allowed Presley to take hard drugs at the same time.
Trying to bolster a defense argument that the superstar received drugs from many sources Neal also asked Cummins about drug screens of Presley while the singer was hospitalized.
Cummins showed the drug screens showed amphetamines in Presley's system though no ampetamines were prescribed while he was in the hospital.
Advertisement
'You're not aware that Mr. Presley was mailed amphetamines from the West Coast'
'No' Cummins answered.
The prosecution said that although Nichopoulos was the attending physician he did not sign the discharge papers as required when Presley was released but defense attorney James F. Neal indicated during cross-examination that Nichopoulos did not sign them because Presley was hospitalized under an assumed name.
'You said Baptist Hospital required a discharge summary' Neal asked.
'Yes' Cummins answered.
'Isn't it a fact that the hospital put a false name on this patient's records' Neal asked.
Cummins said this was true.
In the second hospitalization in 1975 the admission note said that Presley's chief complaint was abdominal problems. Doctors also noted that his face hands and the fronts of his legs were swollen.
In the third hospitalization later the same year Presley was treated for shortness of breath and swelling. A note from Nichopoulos in the medical records said Presley was showing 'progressive malaise.'
Between the second and third hospitalizations prosecutors said Nichopoulos prescribed 1679 addictive pills for Presley over a 205-day period -- 335 amphetamines 816 sedatives and 528 narcotics.
'Did you see any condition that would require this amount of drugs' the prosecutor asked.
Advertisement
Cummins answered the string of questions 'Absolutely not' 'Absolutely none' 'None whatsoever' and 'None.'
Elvis bloated at age 42 was found dead in a bathroom of his Memphis mansion on Aug. 16 1977. A state witness testified earlier that 14 drugs -- including 10 times the maximum accepted level of codeine - were found in blood and tissue samples sent to a California laboratory for analysis.
Although part of the results of the autopsy were revealed the first time the conclusions -- whether Presley died of drug abuse -- remain a secret. Prosecutors say the issue in the trial is whether Nichopoulos overprescribed -- not how Presley died.
Wilson asked Cummins a specialist in internal medicine and chairman of the gastroenterology department at the University of Tennessee Medical School here whether he had an opinion based on his review of the prescription records of whether Presley was addicted to drugs.
'Absolutely. He was addicted' Cummins said.
An emergency room visit wont break the cycle of drug or alcohol addiction but it is an opportune time to start patients on the path to recovery.
Thats the 17 years of ER experience from Dr. Ravi Madasu an emergency medicine specialist at Baptist Memorial Health Cares flagship East Memphis hospital talking. He has treated many who have overdosed and feel they hit a low point.
You see it in their face  theyre scared Madasu said. Theyre in disbelief of what happened sometimes. We hope its the thing that will spark the change.
Now Madasu and his colleagues in the emergency department an area once distanced from addiction care have the right tools to lead patients to long-term treatment.
Baptist partnered with Bartlett-based addiction medicine practice Integrated Addiction Care Associates IAC to launch the Center of Excellence for Addiction Medicine. Both sides feel it was a missing link in combating the opioid crisis and the myriad ER visits it has produced.
Baptist and IAC hope the program will reduce emergency room visits particularly those related to overdoses as those with addiction transition into recovery.
Patients who accept help at the ER are directed to IAC for evaluation and treated for addiction. Baptist is placing the program in both its hospitals and the Baptist Medical Group physician offices.
The program has been going on since the end of August with at least three ER patients daily being looped into the program according to Madasu.
Other health systems and hospitals are looking to bridge the gap between the emergency room and long-term addiction treatment across the U.S. in their own way. But no one else in Memphis is taking the approach Baptist and IAC are said David Stern CEO of IAC. They want this practice to be a model for other Memphis health systems he added.
The center also provides clinical research and physician education in addiction medicine according to Baptist. Stern said the program wants to increase addiction expertise in the West Tennessee area which has become an increased priority in the wake of the opioid crisis.
One treatment  doesnt treat addiction
People who have an addiction may receive excellent care in the emergency department but that care does not address the long-term issue of addiction Stern said.
Physicians traditionally are reluctant to address addiction he said as suggesting a patient has a drug or alcohol problem could offend them.
Its such a primal thing that you dont want to be accusatory Madasu said. Its better if they recognize it themselves.
Another problem is often there isnt a next step once an emergency room physician realizes there is an addiction problem so those physicians dont like to use screening questions that would help identify the substance use problem in the first place according to Stern.
Without follow-up the patient may wind up in the emergency room again following an overdose. Or worse that next overdose is lethal.
Addiction is a chronic brain disease Stern said. One treatment say with opioid overdose antidote Narcan doesnt treat addiction. It just revives a situation where someone may have died but they are alive again. It doesnt rid them of their illness.
A quick turnaround to treatment
Madasu has seen people treated for an overdose return to drug abuse after their time in the ER. Its why beginning the recovery process in the emergency room is key to the centers work he said.
Those patients need to recognize the problem at hand and ask for help before proceeding Madasu said. Its easier for someone who has overdosed on narcotics to do so because they had a life-threatening event he added.
We identify individuals that would be good candidates for the program and want to change Madasu said. Thats imperative. The patient needs to be engaged in it.
Baptist links up with an IAC addiction medicine specialist remotely to figure out a patients needs. The centers service is around the clock with two IAC doctors rotating shifts to be on call whenever Madasu and others in the ER need help Stern said.
Baptist doctors already have access to various other specialists through telemedicine so it made sense to also bring addiction specialists expertise into the emergency room he said.
Thanks to the telemedicine access the patient is able to meet an addiction specialist on-screen and get a next-day appointment set up.
Every patient that has been processed in this way has shown up the next day Stern said.
Getting addiction treatment from IAC is more like going to a primary care physician office due to its accessibility for Memphians said Baptist PR Director Ayoka Pond and is covered by most insurers including TennCare. This prevents the need to go to a far-flung treatment facility for months on end.
Theyre able to get care in their environment and learn how to cope in their environment Pond said.
