Addiction comes at a high cost.
There's the high cost to the addicts themselves the fleeting highs and aching lows that feeling your life is unraveling and realizing you're holding the string the fade away the trips to rehab or maybe sometimes eventually to the morgue. Then there's the high cost to the family of addicts to the grieving parents to the alienated siblings and  worst of all  to the children whose care takes a backseat to the addiction.
There's the high cost of the funerals that has nothing to do with the price of the casket.
Today The Commercial Appeal has two stories about addiction. First there's the devastating news from our Bob Mehr that Memphis singer-songwriter former Tigers basketball player recovering alcohol addict and St. John's United Methodist associate pastor of recovery ministries John Kilzer died in an out-of-state rehab facility. Second the city of Memphis is following others including Shelby County and Tennessee in suing pharmaceutical makers and distributors for allegedly fueling the opioid crisis currently ravaging the nation our Phillip Jackson reports.
I'd only recently become acquainted with Kilzer  who was scheduled to play this year's Beale Street Music Festival  after featuring a song from his new album Scars in one of The 901's closing Fadeout numbers in January his song American Blues fades out today's column. Bob pulls back the veil on Kilzer's inner struggles
Though St. Johns did not disclose any details about the circumstances of his death several of Kilzers friends and associates confirmed that the musician  whod battled alcohol issues much of his life but been sober since 2000  had been struggling with his addiction again. In recent days Kilzer had checked into an out-of-state rehab facility where his body was found on Tuesday they said. The news left those who knew Kilzer  in the Memphis music scene and the church and recovery communities where he was a beloved figure  in a state of shock and sadness.
Again addiction  whether alcohol opioids or whatever else  comes at a high cost.
But maybe it'll surprise you to know there's also a high cost to governments including Memphis'. The Shelby County Health Department which has a very good and helpful website on opioid addiction sums up the local impact
Opioid-related deaths are consistently rising throughout Shelby County with rates doubling in just three years. There were 854 opioid-related emergency department visits in Shelby County in 2018 alone and in 2017 more Shelby County residents died from opioid overdose than in car accidents.
That's just deaths though. Shelby County and Memphis together spend millions of dollars yearly on policing transporting sentencing imprisoning and treating people for addiction.
But who is responsible Although we can't overlook personal responsibility for addiction the Memphis lawsuit argues that pharmaceutical companies share in the responsibility accusing them of intentionally underplaying the addictive qualities of the opiates.
If that's the case the addicts their families and local governments shouldn't be left to bear the cost alone opioid addiction should come at a high cost to Big Pharma too.
