It wasn't long ago that patients arriving at the emergency department of Baptist Memorial Hospital-Memphis with bone fractures migraines and other maladies could count on getting potent opioid medication to alleviate their pain.
Not anymore.
Amid a deadly epidemic of opioid addiction gripping the nation Baptist's emergency department is charting a new course in treating pain. Instead of turning first to such drugs as morphine or oxycodone ER doctors and nurse practitioners operate under a new protocol emphasizing the use when appropriate of non-addictive alternatives like intravenous acetaminophen lidocaine patches muscle relaxers and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory medication.
It's a program Baptist calls Opioid Light and so far it's yielding major benefits hospital officials say.
COMPLETE COVERAGE The science of opioids
Since its launch in March the number of ER patients receiving opioids has dropped by 50 percent while the total number of milligrams prescribed is down 58 percent. At the same time patient satisfaction with the treatment of their pain has risen 30 percent according to the hospital.
We just had to change our culture said Julie Bennett critical staff pharmacist at Baptist Memphis.
MoreShelby County unveils strategy for opioid crisis response
Baptist isn't alone among Memphis-area hospitals in working to rein in the use of opioids.
Regional Medical Center is collecting data to guide the possible development of a similar program spokeswoman Angie Golding said. Also Methodist Le Bonheur Healthcare has created a policy that reduces the number of days for which emergency department physicians will prescribe opioids the company said in a prepared statement.
If our medical professionals suspect patients may need help with an addiction we work closely with mental health facilities that offer programs that they could benefit from and improve their mental health the statement continued.
The need for the programs is readily apparent proponents say. Opioid addiction has become so rampant that President Donald Trump last fall declared it a public health emergency. In Tennessee where overdoses claim at least three lives a day Gov. Bill Haslam last week announced a 30 million plan to fight the opioid addiction problem.
In January TennCare the state's Medicaid program further tightened its limits on the amount of opioid medication that participants can be prescribed.
In addition to morphine and oxycodone the opioids most typically tied to addiction include fentanyl hydrocodone and Percocet. Many patients who become hooked on the prescription drugs turn to heroin after being unable to get further prescriptions.
The Memphis area so far has been spared the worst of the epidemic. Opioid prescriptions in Shelby County totaled 73.6 per 100 people during 2016 less than half the rates at which the painkillers were dispensed in many other Tennessee counties according to data collected by the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
Still the problem is significant here said Dr. Marilyn McLeod medical director of the emergency department at Baptist Memphis.
It's not an unusual day when two or three people are dropped off in the ED not breathing because of an opioid overdose she said.
Opioids became pervasive in part because doctors saw them as the best means to get patients' pain under control McLeod said. And in many cases the reimbursements physicians received were based in part on patient satisfaction with their pain management.
Many doctors also believed  wrongly as it turns out  that if patients were truly in pain when they took opioids they wouldn't get addicted she said.
We thought we were doing the right thing McLeod said.
What has become abundantly clear is that the problem of opioid addiction breaches all demographics regardless of income and education levels.
Anybody could get pain medicine for a few days and turn into an addict McLeod said.
To help head off addiction Baptist began educating emergency department doctors and nurse practitioners on alternatives to opioids some of which are more effective in managing pain.
Although it's the source of only a small percentage of prescriptions at the hospital the emergency department is key because it's where patients often get their first medications McLeod said.
The staff developed a list of alternatives to opioids that could be used depending on a patient's diagnosis. McLeod emphasizes there are many ailments and injuries that still will require opioids.
If you come in here and you have stage IV cancer you're going to get opioids for your pain she said.
The cases in which non-opioid alternatives are most likely to be used include fractures abdominal pain muscular and skeletal pain renal cholic and migraines McLeod said.
In cases in which opioids are prescribed emergency room doctors often are prescribing fewer days' worth of pills. Instead of the seven-day supply formerly provided less than three days' worth is typical now.
In addition to reducing the number of patients getting opioids and the doses prescribed the Opioid Light program also seeks to reset patients' expectations about pain management hospital officials say.
Sometimes the best thing for a patient is not what they want McLeod said. Switching to alternatives is more work but it's the right thing to do.
Still amid the growing awareness of the addiction problem more and more patients are asking that they not be given opioids Bennett and McLeod say.
Once results from the program are fully measured the initiative could expand to other departments of the hospital McLeod said. Preventing addiction among patients is paramount.
Once they get addicted we're behind the eight ball she said.
