Families addicts share stories of both hope and desperation
We cannot arrest our way out of this law enforcement says
The statistics are staggering the stories heartbreaking
More than 52000 overdose deaths nationwide in 2015 more than 33000 of them from opioids. It's the equivalent of 91 deaths per day one every 16 minutes -- the same as one 747 airliner crash every 4.5 days assuming the average 416 passengers carried by a 747.
That's unreal isn't it when you think of it that way says Tammy Reynolds an agent with the Mississippi Bureau of Narcotics.
But it is real Reynolds and a team of state and local representatives conceded Tuesday evening. They came to Landers Center in Southaven for what was dubbed a Town Hall Rally to discuss the state's ongoing opioid drug epidemic. The stop was part of series of statewide meetings that will continue into December.
 Read more Mississippi Kroger team to fight opioid epidemic
 Related Tennessee Shelby County look to sue as opioid costs mount
The meetings sponsored by a coalition of state agencies in conjunction with the federal Drug Enforcement Administration and FBI underscores the fact that the national numbers are equally grim in Mississippi where heroin-related overdoses rose 2000 percent from 2013 to 2016. DeSoto County leads the state in heroin deaths with 23 last year and 19 already this year.
More than 100 came to the Southaven gathering many from Memphis and surrounding areas. Those in attendance were a mix of law enforcement and health care professionals recovering addicts and families desperately seeking answers that everyone admitted they didn't have.
We want to bring some hope some thinking some ideas to the table said Steve Parker deputy director of the Mississippi Board of Pharmacy.
Reynolds said the problem cuts across the social spectrum and overcoming the stigma of drug abuse and working together are pieces of the answer.
There are parents today who are losing sons and daughters there are pregnant women who are shooting up heroin and overdosing she said. We have grandparents in epidemic proportions who are raising grandchildren even great-grandchildren.
So we're coming together today with you guys because we don't have all the answers. Law enforcement doesn't the Department of Mental Health doesn't providers who issue prescription drugs don't. We hope by enlightening you to what we're seeing we can all work together to find solutions.
 Read more Opioid antidote becoming more easily available for general public
The stories shared during the two-hour exchange were a brutal assault on the senses -- a desperate father speaking in a broken voice about driving his son to Murfreesboro Tennessee for treatment just to get him away from his daily influences closer to home and a family whose child overdosed while waiting to get into treatment only to be released from the hospital directly into a treatment facility before he could use again.
And then there was Debra Ward sitting on the front row and holding close a photo of her daughter who died a year ago at 20 years old. She died from a heart valve infection she got from using a dirty needle to inject heroin. Ward held on her lap an 8-by-10 photo of her smiling daughter and granddaughter.
At least I was left with a little piece of her Ward said referring to the granddaughter now in her custody.
In depth As drug-related heart infections climb doctors weigh ethics of operating
Panelists who could often only offer their sympathy said reducing the number of opioids prescribed is part of the solution. Prescription pills often fall into the wrong hands and lead to addiction and ultimately heroin use since they said heroin offers the same high at a lower price.
Statistics cited by Reynolds show the U.S. which accounts for about 5 percent of the world's population consumes about 80 percent of the opioids manufactured worldwide. The percentage includes 99.7 percent of all hydrocodone products.
Making naloxone a medication designed to block and reverse opioid effects more accessible was identified as another part of the solution.
One tool that can't be considered a solution all agreed is criminalizing drug addiction. Though DeSoto County Sheriff Bill Rasco called addiction an epidemic we have to get under control Reynolds the Bureau of Narcotics agent agent said what all were thinking
We cannot Reynolds emphasized arrest our way out of this.
The next Town Hall Rally is scheduled for Aug. 15 in Columbus. An Oct. 3 rally is set for Oxford.
